This type declaration [coresponds to this npm package](https://www.npmjs.com/package/tinymce)

# Imporvments

- It now matches the [newer versions of typescript since 1.5](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/namespaces-and-modules.html) that suggest exporting a namespace as an es6 module rather than declaring a module and exporting that.

First tiny PR for https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/issues/14418. Turns out this definition is actually pretty good, but I always ran into the issue with `Duplex` and `Transform` type incompatibilities and this will fix that. I also removed `protected` from the `_read` and `_write` methods, purely because you can do `implements` with a protected class (e.g. `class Duplex extends Readable implements Writable`). There's also the minor fact that you could end up with differing `@types/node` versions running and `protected` would break that anyway.

I did try to run `dtslint`, but there's 1000 other issues to fix so maybe that's for a future PR. 

Edit: Oh, I also moved `isTTY` onto a `Socket` interface used in `process`. That more closely represents reality, but I can change that if needed. Having `isTTY` on the stream seemed wrong.

title: three: Make THREE non-global
body:
@gyohk @florentpoujol @SereznoKot @omni360 @ivoisbelongtous @piranha771 I'd appreciate if any of you could review. Thanks in advance.

I was running into duplicate identifier issues as a result of using `npm link`, as described in this issue https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/11916#issuecomment-257130001 . Following the advice of @mhegazy in that thread, we should make the definitions not establish a global `THREE` namespace by default.

Now if you import three as a module you do not get a global `THREE` namespace defined. You will still get a global namespace if you use a `/// reference` directive. @mrdoob this change might interest you, I know sometimes people reach out to you regarding using three.js with TypeScript.

99% of the change is just removing the `namespace THREE` nesting. The exceptions are as follows:
 - move core THREE members from `types/three/index.d.ts` into `types/three/three-core.d.ts`
 - consolidation of contributors and metadata into `types/three/index.d.ts`
 - consolidation of references for tests in to `types/three/test/references.d.ts`
 - last line of `types/three/detector.d.ts` (export as namespace)
 - last line of `types/three/index.d.ts` (export as namespace)
 - moved some declarations from `types/three/test/three-tests-setup.ts` to `types/three/three-examples.d.ts` These were low quality definitions that were only in tests before, but they're not wrong afaik, they just use `any`.

This has potential to be breaking for users of `three` definitions who rely on it being global, but global use **is** still working as can be seen from the tests so it may depend on how they're importing the definitions.

As an example of something that could break, `openjscad` was augmenting the `THREE` namespace but that requires using `declare module` now, instead of `declare namespace`. @danmarshall Can you review my fix to `openjscad`?

title: @types/node: fix dns.lookup() definitions
body:
This is rebased pull request https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/15103

### List of changes

* Fix `dns.lookup()` return type: instead of `string` return `void`. 
* Add signatures where `options` is object. There are 3 cases:
  1. Option `all` doesn't exist or `false`, then callback is `(err: NodeJS.ErrnoException, address: string, family: number) => void`.
  2. Option `all` is `true`, then callback is `(err: NodeJS.ErrnoException, addresses: Address[]) => void`.
  3. Options `all` has `boolean` type (for example, user assigns to option result of some function where we don't known exact literal type (`true` or `false`) at compile time), then callback is union of 1 and 2.
* Change type of `error` callback argument from `Error` to `NodeJS.ErrnoException`: https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/98e54b0bd4854bdb3e2949d1b6b20d6777fb7cde/lib/dns.js#L184
* Export [getaddrinfo flags](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v6.x/docs/api/dns.html#dns_supported_getaddrinfo_flags).
* Add tests for this cases.
* Apply changes to the following `Node.js` versions: 7, 6, 4.
